Class MorseCodeTree

java.lang.Object
MorseCodeTree
All Implemented Interfaces:
LinkedConverterTreeInterface
public class MorseCodeTree extends Object implements LinkedConverterTreeInterface
This class represents a Binary Search Tree holding various strings, each representing a letter of the English alphabet. The positions of these strings are determined by Morse code, allowing the user to easily add and retrieve letters, assisting in the conversion of Morse code to English
Author:
Evan Song

    • buildTree

      public void buildTree()
      Constructs a tree, with letters inserted into the tree based on a Morse code map. This method uses individual calls of the insert method for each letter, which is slightly inefficient. In the future, a combination of arrays and for loops would be more fficient. However, the code works, which is what matters at heart
      Specified by:

    • insert

      public LinkedConverterTreeInterface insert​(Object code, Object result)
      The backbone of the buildTree method. This method inserts a new node into the tree using the recursive addNode method, starting at the root of the tree
      Specified by:

    • addNode

      public void addNode​(TreeNode recursiveRoot, Object code, Object letter)
      A recursive method which adds a Node to the tree. It does this by taking the first character of the code and then recursively calling itself, but with a new root of the child of the current root based on that first character, and a new code of the original code without the first character. Once there is only one character left in the code, it adds a new node to the current node, based on that character, and then stops calling itself.
      Specified by:
      addNode in interface LinkedConverterTreeInterface
      Parameters:
      recursiveRoot - The node that the function is currently referencing, which will have a new child added to it if code only has one character left
      code - The Morse code equivalent of the letter to be added, for example, 'l' would have a code of '.-..'
      letter - The letter to be added into the tree. Standard English alphabet only, with no numbers or special characters

    • fetch

      public Object fetch​(String code)
      Similar to the insert method, this method retrieves the data stored in a specific node from the tree, without altering or removing the node itself. It calls the fetchNode recursive method starting at the root of the tree
      Specified by:
      fetch in interface LinkedConverterTreeInterface
      Parameters:
      code - The Morse code equivalent of the letter to be fetched, for example, 'l' would have a code of '.-..'
      Returns:
      Object The data stored in the node, always a String (specifically a letter) in this case.

    • fetchNode

      public Object fetchNode​(TreeNode recursiveRoot, Object code)
      A recursive method that works similarly to addNode, which follows the same steps as addNode except that once it reaches the last character in code, it retrieves the data held by the relevant child, instead of adding a new node.
      Specified by:
      fetchNode in interface LinkedConverterTreeInterface
      Parameters:
      recursiveRoot - The node that the function is currently referencing, which will have a its child returned if code only has one character left
      code - The Morse code equivalent of the letter to be fetched, for example, 'l' would have a code of '.-..'
      Returns:
      Object The data stored in the node, always a String (specifically a letter) in this case.

    • LNRoutputTraversal

      public void LNRoutputTraversal​(TreeNode recursiveRoot, ArrayList list)
      A recursive method that checks whether the current node has a left child, and recursively calls itself using that node as a root if so. It then adds its own data to the list, and then repeats the first step using the right node.
      Specified by:
      LNRoutputTraversal in interface LinkedConverterTreeInterface
      Parameters:
      recursiveRoot - The node being checked, which will eventually add its data to the list
      list - The ArrayList that is being added to, which will eventually be returned by the toArrayList method
